        <img class="biography-image desktopDisplay" src="img/vertical.jpg">
        <div class="biography-text">
            <p>
                Born in Washington, D.C. to a musical family, Leah Plave’s love for music and fine arts was encouraged from a young age.  While living in D.C., she performed regularly with the Metropolitan Camerata, the Masterworks Festival Orchestra, and the Maryland Classic Youth Orchestra. She studied with National Symphony Orchestra cellist Mark Evans and kept a private studio of cello students ranging from young to adult musicians.
            </p>
            <p>
                Leah Plave is pursuing her Bachelor of Music at The University of Cincinnati College-Conservatory of Music, where she studies with internationally acclaimed cellist Yehuda Hanani.  She is a strings teacher at MYCincinnati, an El Sistema-inspired music program for youth in Cincinnati. Ms. Plave is also an active freelance musician in the Ohio area and frequent recitalist. She is currently living in Budapest, Hungary, where she studies at Zeneakademia (Franz Liszt Academy of Music) with Professor Csaba Onczay.
            </p>
            <p>
                Ms. Plave’s primary interest lies in in chamber music. She was recently one of 15 Young Artists to receive a chamber music fellowship at the Manchester Music Festival, where she played alongside Trio Solisti, Ariel Rudiakov, and Joana Genova-Rudiakov.  She also performed as an artist in residence at the Carey Institute for Global Good in New York during the Helderberg Chamber Music Series.
            </p>
        </div>
